@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Variables and Inputs";
}

<style>
.lesson-container { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding-bottom: 3rem; }
.lesson-intro { margin-bottom: 2rem; color: #8b949e; font-size: 1.1rem; }
.example-card { background: var(--card-bg, #21262d); border: 1px solid var(--border, #30363d); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
.example-card h3 { margin-top: 0; color: #e6edf3; }
.explanation { color: #8b949e; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.demo-box { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2); border: 1px solid var(--border, #30363d); border-radius: 6px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
code { background: var(--code-bg); padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 4px; color: #e6edf3; font-family: monospace; }
</style>

<div class="lesson-container">
  <h2>Variables and Inputs in Angular</h2>
  <p class="lesson-intro">Angular provides several ways to declare variables and receive data from parent components. Here is how they compare:</p>

  <div class="example-card">
    <h3>1. Normal Variables</h3>
    <p class="explanation">
      Standard TypeScript class properties. They are not deeply reactive on their own outside of Angular's Zone.js change detection cycle. You use standard interpolation <code>{{ property }}</code> to display them.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-box">
      <p><strong>Title:</strong> MVC Port Title</p>
      <p><strong>Description:</strong> This is a static representation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="example-card">
    <h3>2. Signal Variables</h3>
    <p class="explanation">
      Introduced in Angular 16+, signals are reactive wrappers around a value. They tell Angular exactly when they change, making your app extremely fast. In the template, you MUST call them as a function: <code>{{ signalExample() }}</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-box">
      <p><strong>Value:</strong> Signal value here</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="example-card">
    <h3>3. Optional Signal Inputs</h3>
    <p class="explanation">
      The modern replacement for <code>@@Input()</code>. This acts exactly like a <code>[Parameter]</code> in Blazor. It receives data from the parent component. Because it's a signal, it's read-only from inside this component, and reactive.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-box">
      <p><strong>Value provided by Parent:</strong> Optional Input</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="example-card">
    <h3>4. Required Signal Inputs</h3>
    <p class="explanation">
      Like <code>[Parameter, EditorRequired]</code> in Blazor. It enforces that the parent component <strong>must</strong> pass a value, otherwise Angular throws a runtime error. It cannot have a default value.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-box">
      <p><strong>Required Value from Parent:</strong> Required Input</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
